To enumerate users on a Linux system using a C++ program, we can utilize the POSIX APIs to access the system's user database. The `getpwent` function is used to read the password database and retrieve information about each user one at a time.

Here's a simple C++ program that lists all users in the Linux system:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <pwd.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>

int main() {
    struct passwd *user_entry;

    // Set the password file pointer to the beginning
    setpwent();

    // Read the password database entries until there are no more
    while ((user_entry = getpwent()) != NULL) {
        std::cout << "Username: " << user_entry->pw_name << std::endl;
        std::cout << "User ID (UID): " << user_entry->pw_uid << std::endl;
        std::cout << "Group ID (GID): " << user_entry->pw_gid << std::endl;
        std::cout << "Home Directory: " << user_entry->pw_dir << std::endl;
        std::cout << "Shell: " << user_entry->pw_shell << std::endl;
        std::cout << "------------------------------------" << std::endl;
    }

    // Close the password file
    endpwent();

    return 0;
}
```

This program makes use of the following functions:

- `setpwent()`: Resets the reading of the password database to the beginning.
- `getpwent()`: Reads the next entry from the password database.
- `endpwent()`: Closes the password database file when done.

To compile and run this program, use the following commands in the terminal:

```bash
g++ -o enumerate_users enumerate_users.cpp
./enumerate_users
```

The program will output the username, user ID (UID), group ID (GID), home directory, and login shell for each user found in the system's password database.

Please note that this program needs to be run with sufficient privileges to access the password database. If certain user information is protected or the program is not run with the necessary permissions, it may not be able to retrieve or display all details for every user.

