To determine if an Android device is low-end, you generally need to consider several factors such as its hardware specifications, software version, and performance capabilities. There's no single code to input that will tell you if a device is low-end, but you can infer this from various indicators. Here's a method that combines different checks:

```java
public boolean isLowEndDevice(Context context) {
    // Check for minimum hardware specifications that are indicative of low-end devices.
    // These specifications can vary over time as technology advances.
    final int MIN_CPU_CORES = 2;
    final int MIN_RAM_MB = 1024; // 1GB
    final long MIN_STORAGE_MB = 8000; // 8GB

    // Check CPU cores
    int cores = Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors();
    if (cores < MIN_CPU_CORES) {
        return true;
    }

    // Check RAM
    ActivityManager activityManager = (ActivityManager) context.getSystemService(Context.ACTIVITY_SERVICE);
    if (activityManager != null) {
        ActivityManager.MemoryInfo memoryInfo = new ActivityManager.MemoryInfo();
        activityManager.getMemoryInfo(memoryInfo);
        long totalMemory = memoryInfo.totalMem / (1024 * 1024);
        if (totalMemory < MIN_RAM_MB) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    // Check internal storage
    StatFs statFs = new StatFs(Environment.getDataDirectory().getAbsolutePath());
    long availableStorage = (statFs.getBlockSizeLong() * statFs.getBlockCountLong()) / (1024 * 1024);
    if (availableStorage < MIN_STORAGE_MB) {
        return true;
    }

    // Check for old OS versions which might indicate an older, lower-end device
    int sdkInt = android.os.Build.VERSION.SDK_INT;
    int latestSdkInt = android.os.Build.VERSION_CODES.R; // Update this value as new versions are released
    if (sdkInt < latestSdkInt - 3) { // If it's more than 3 versions behind the latest
        return true;
    }

    // Check for other performance bottlenecks like animation power and image resizing capabilities
    // This is more of a heuristic approach and might not be accurate for all devices
    // You can use profiling tools or specific performance metrics to check this

    // If none of the above conditions are met, the device is likely not low-end
    return false;
}
```
This method uses several heuristics to determine if a device is low-end, including checking the number of CPU cores, the amount of RAM, the internal storage capacity, and the OS version. However, remember that these benchmarks may change over time as new devices and technology standards emerge.

Please note that accessing some of this information might require specific permissions in your Android application manifest, and you should handle runtime permissions accordingly. Also, the method is a simplified approach and may not cover all possible scenarios or device specifications.

