To correct the pattern, it's important to understand what you want to achieve with the split. If you are trying to split the string by punctuation, a corrected version of your pattern could look something like this:

```php
$description = "Dangerous places are good.";
$parts = preg_split('/([^\p{P}]+) | (\p{P}+\s+\p{P}*) | (\p{P}+$)/', $description, -1, PREG_SPLIT_NO_EMPTY);
```

However, the pattern above still contains spaces that might not be intended and could cause incorrect splitting. A more typical pattern to split by punctuation while keeping the words might be:

```php
$description = "Dangerous places are good.";
$parts = preg_split('/\p{P}+/', $description, -1, PREG_SPLIT_NO_EMPTY);
```

This will split the string `$description` at every point where one or more punctuation characters occur. The `\p{P}` is a Unicode property escape that matches any kind of punctuation character, and `+` means one or more occurrences.

If you want to preserve the whitespace as well, you might want to exclude it from the split:

```php
$description = "Dangerous places are good.";
$parts = preg_split('/(?<!\s)\p{P}+(?!\s)/', $description, -1, PREG_SPLIT_NO_EMPTY);
```

This pattern uses negative lookbehind `(?<!\s)` and negative lookahead `(?!\s)` to avoid splitting at spaces before and after punctuation. Note that this pattern assumes you want to keep words and spaces but not punctuation.

Please adjust the regular expression according to your exact needs, as the right pattern depends on the rules you want to apply for splitting the string.

