   import AlertContext from './AlertContext';

   const Modal = () => {
     const { open, content, hideAlert } = useContext(AlertContext);

     if (!open) return null;

     return (
       <div className="modal">
         <div className="modal-content">{content}</div>
         <button onClick={hideAlert}>Close</button>
       </div>
     );
   };

   export default Modal;
   ```

4. **Use the Context:**
   Anywhere in your app, you can now use the context to show or hide the popup. Just use the `useContext` hook to get access to the `showAlert` and `hideAlert` functions.

   ```javascript
   import React, { useContext } from 'react';
   import AlertContext from './AlertContext';

   const SomeComponent = () => {
     const { showAlert } = useContext(AlertContext);

     return (
       <button onClick={() => showAlert('This is an alert!')}>
         Show Alert
       </button>
     );
   };

   export default SomeComponent;
   ```

5. **Wrap Your Application:**
   Finally, wrap your application with the `AlertProvider` you created. This will make the context available throughout your component tree.

   ```javascript
   // App.js
   import React from 'react';
   import AlertProvider from './AlertProvider';
   import SomeComponent from './SomeComponent';
   import Modal from './Modal';

   const App = () => {
     return (
       <AlertProvider>
         <SomeComponent />
         <Modal />
       </AlertProvider>
     );
   };

   export default App;
   ```

This is a simplified example, and you'll likely need to adjust it to fit your application's structure and styling requirements. The modal logic can be enhanced with animations, additional state management, and more complex behaviors based on your needs.
